A Gentle Introduction to R and statistics (CC3 Statistics Workshop)

Chapter 3. Inferential statistics

Inferential statistics refer to the type of statistics that allows you to reach beyond your observation and infer what the population might think about a phenomenon. Furthermore, inferential statistics allows you to judge whether an observed difference between groups in your data only occurs by chance or can be generalized to a wider population.

3.1 Normality test

To conduct inferential statistics tests, we have to start by checking the normality of your data (whether your data is normally distributed, or the distribution of data is symmetrical and bell-shaped ). If you search online, some might tell you that you could skip this test and assume that your data is normally distributed if your sample size is larger than 30 because of the central limit theorem. However, it is always a good idea to run a normality test to choose the right statistical test, since this allows you to obtain more accurate and reliable results.

There are many normality tests available, but here we will use the Shapiro-Wilks test. The function for Shapiro-Wilks test is in the stats package. Using the same sat.act data set, the code and result of Shapiro-Wilks test of the ACT scores is as follows:

# load data
test_score <- psych::sat.act
#load package
library(stats) 

# Syntax: shapiro.test(data)  
# Note that the data should contain only one column of numeric data
shapiro.test(test_score$ACT)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  test_score$ACT
## W = 0.95996, p-value = 6.879e-13

The function gives us 2 outputs: a W value, and a p-value. We should focus on the p-value. If the p-value is larger than 0.05, weve failed to reject the null hypothesis that the sample is normally distributed. If the p-value is smaller than 0.05, we can reject the null hypothesis that the sample is normally distributed.

In this case, the p-value is much smaller than 0.05, rejecting the null hypothesis. This means that the sample is not normally distributed.

We could verify this with a distribution plot, using the ggdensity() function from the ggpubr package.

library(ggpubr)
ggdensity(test_score$ACT)

The distribution of the data looks like a bell-shaped curve, but tilting (skewed) towards the right. Thus, we say that this data is not normally distributed. Using the same method, we also get that the SATQ and SATV data is not normally distributed as well.
